          "prompt_html": "<h1>NOTE COMPLETION 52</h1><p><strong>Questions 31 - 40</strong></p><p>Complete the notes below.</p><p>Write <strong>ONE WORD ONLY</strong> for each answer.</p><p><em>The Chimp Paradox</em> by Professor Steve Peters</p><p><strong>The basic idea of</strong> <strong><em>The Chimp Paradox</em></strong></p><p>Sometimes, humans behave a bit like chimpanzees!</p><p>According to Peters, the brain contains two parts: ‘human’ and ‘chimp’</p><p>The ‘human’ is the part of the brain that:</p><ul><li>is usually <blank data-qid=\"q31\"/></li><li>likes to have <blank data-qid=\"q32\"/></li></ul><p>The ‘chimp’</p><ul><li>is more <blank data-qid=\"q33\"/></li><li>than the human</li><li>can be a friend or an enemy</li></ul><p>Having these two very different parts of the brain often leads to a <blank data-qid=\"q34\"/>; this is the ‘chimp paradox’</p><p><strong>Examples of the chimp paradox</strong></p><ul><li>entering a room full of <blank data-qid=\"q35\"/> and being unsure how to react</li><li>deciding whether to complete a dull task or to <blank data-qid=\"q36\"/></li></ul><p><strong>Applications of The Chimp Paradox in sport</strong></p><p>The Chimp Paradox famously helped convince a well-known <blank data-qid=\"q37\"/> to continue</p><p>She says the ‘chimp’ approach helped her become a <blank data-qid=\"q38\"/></p><p>Snooker player Ronnie O’Sullivan said that Peters’ ideas enabled him to deal with <blank data-qid=\"q39\"/></p><p>Peters encouraged O’Sullivan to find time for <blank data-qid=\"q40\"/>, which he enjoyed</p>",
